5.
    a.
        Add to the sample NaOH. Observe that a blue precipitate forms. This indicates that there are Copper (II) ions. If it does not form, then the test shows that there are no such ions.
    b?
        Copper metal forms as there are free Cu^{2+} ions in the solution. When power is turned on, the negative electrode becomes negatively charged as electrons move from the positive to the negative electrode as a result of the power becoming turned on. There is an electrostatic attraction between the copper ions in the solution and the negatively charged negative electrode. So, the copper ions move to the negative electrode and collect to form copper metal.
